1
00:01:48,900 --> 00:01:50,789
Can you just listen up?

2
00:01:51,460 --> 00:01:52,586
Guys?

3
00:01:53,940 --> 00:01:57,865
We got 2,000 feet,
600 vertical meters

4
00:01:58,420 --> 00:01:59,910
to Camp Four.

5
00:02:00,540 --> 00:02:04,511
It's roped all the way,
so I know you can make it.

6
00:02:05,140 --> 00:02:06,426
Once we get to
the yellow band,

7
00:02:06,500 --> 00:02:07,700
we're gonna regroup,

8
00:02:08,300 --> 00:02:10,985
put on the masks,
turn on the gas.

9
00:02:11,060 --> 00:02:12,710
Make sense?

10
00:03:04,700 --> 00:03:07,180
325 dollars a bottle.

11
00:03:07,260 --> 00:03:08,261
For oxygen?

12
00:03:08,340 --> 00:03:09,501
That's daylight robbery!

13
00:03:09,580 --> 00:03:11,901
Yeah, well, he's
cornered the market, he's got it.

14
00:03:11,980 --> 00:03:14,904
He reckons there's gonna be
20 teams at Base Camp this season.

15
00:03:15,020 --> 00:03:16,020
Twenty teams?

16
00:03:16,060 --> 00:03:17,471
I mean, with all
the Sherpas and porters,

17
00:03:17,540 --> 00:03:19,941
it's gonna be
a squeeze up there.

18
00:03:20,420 --> 00:03:23,026
Well, that's a scrum on
the ropes, right there.

19
00:03:23,100 --> 00:03:25,228
What is this?
It's Helen's.

20
00:03:25,300 --> 00:03:27,382
It's a little
decoration for the mess tent.

21
00:03:27,460 --> 00:03:28,461
You can wear them
in your hair.

22
00:03:28,540 --> 00:03:29,541
I'll have that.
Thank you.

23
00:03:29,660 --> 00:03:31,503
Okay, I got some news.

24
00:03:32,100 --> 00:03:33,989
We got Krakauer.

25
00:03:34,060 --> 00:03:35,903
You stole him
from Scott Fischer?

26
00:03:35,980 --> 00:03:37,311
No, he made up
his own mind.

27
00:03:37,420 --> 00:03:38,831
Good job, Rob!

28
00:03:39,460 --> 00:03:41,827
How much is he
paying you, Rob?

29
00:03:41,900 --> 00:03:44,267
Well, he's only
paying for his airfare

30
00:03:44,340 --> 00:03:47,344
but we get 5,000
words in the magazine

31
00:03:47,420 --> 00:03:49,229
and our picture on
the front cover. Huh?

32
00:03:49,300 --> 00:03:51,906
That makes it all worthwhile.
Right there.

33
00:03:51,980 --> 00:03:53,311
Well, if you get
him to the top.

34
00:03:53,380 --> 00:03:54,586
If?

35
00:03:54,660 --> 00:03:56,389
If? How can you
say that to me?

36
00:03:56,460 --> 00:03:57,586
There you go.
You all right?

37
00:03:57,660 --> 00:03:59,264
Thanks, Guy.
Cheers, mate.

38
00:03:59,340 --> 00:04:00,944
Hey!
Hello!

39
00:04:02,340 --> 00:04:04,229
You all right?
Oh, yeah, how are you?

40
00:04:04,300 --> 00:04:05,665
Me? I'm good.
Oh, look at you!

41
00:04:05,780 --> 00:04:07,703
I know, I'm big.

42
00:04:07,780 --> 00:04:09,703
Here you go.
You good?

43
00:04:09,780 --> 00:04:11,669
Yeah, you know,
I'm just gonna miss you.

44
00:04:11,740 --> 00:04:12,946
Come on.

45
00:04:15,820 --> 00:04:17,663
- Let's go, Guy.
Mmm-hmm.

46
00:04:18,180 --> 00:04:20,865
Just go careful,
all right?

47
00:04:20,940 --> 00:04:22,430
It's...
Please, my love.

48
00:04:22,940 --> 00:04:24,783
Come on.
Please don't worry.

49
00:04:24,900 --> 00:04:26,743
It's just the doing
nothing back here

50
00:04:26,820 --> 00:04:28,151
that's making me worry.

51
00:04:28,260 --> 00:04:29,261
You're not doing nothing.

52
00:04:29,340 --> 00:04:30,626
No, but...

53
00:04:30,700 --> 00:04:31,826
What?

54
00:04:32,380 --> 00:04:34,223
It's the waiting for you.

55
00:04:34,780 --> 00:04:36,942
For him.
Her.

56
00:04:37,060 --> 00:04:38,505
Her.
Her.

57
00:04:41,300 --> 00:04:43,985
Just be back for
the birth, Rob Hall.

58
00:04:45,380 --> 00:04:47,144
You try and stop me.

59
00:04:47,580 --> 00:04:48,991
<i>This is a final call</i>

60
00:04:49,060 --> 00:04:52,064
<i>for Air New Zealand
Flight 7419 to Kathmandu.</i>

61
00:04:52,140 --> 00:04:54,381
Okay, I love you.
Go, or I'll cry.

62
00:04:54,460 --> 00:04:55,700
Go.

63
00:05:20,060 --> 00:05:21,186
Yeah.

64
00:05:21,700 --> 00:05:22,826
That all you got?

65
00:05:22,940 --> 00:05:24,226
Yeah, that's it.

66
00:05:24,700 --> 00:05:26,668
I think
we're over here.

67
00:05:35,020 --> 00:05:37,341
Hey, what outfit
you guys with?

68
00:05:37,420 --> 00:05:38,460
Uh, Adventure Consultants.

69
00:05:38,540 --> 00:05:39,621
Ah, good. Me too.

70
00:05:39,700 --> 00:05:40,826
Ah.
I'm Beck.

71
00:05:40,900 --> 00:05:42,743
Beck Weathers.
Doug Hansen.

72
00:05:43,260 --> 00:05:44,944
Jon Krakauer.
How you doing?

73
00:05:45,020 --> 00:05:46,545
Good.
Are you, uh...

74
00:05:46,620 --> 00:05:49,351
Krakauer from <i>Outside</i> magazine?
Yep.

75
00:05:49,420 --> 00:05:50,501
Really?

76
00:05:50,580 --> 00:05:52,662
What are you doing?
Writing or climbing or what?

77
00:05:52,740 --> 00:05:54,902
Little bit of both.
Hmm.

78
00:05:54,980 --> 00:05:57,551
Well, I'll let you know
how the summit goes, okay?

79
00:05:57,620 --> 00:05:59,384
No need.
I'll be there.

80
00:05:59,460 --> 00:06:00,791
Ah, we'll see.

81
00:06:16,620 --> 00:06:18,907
What do you do when
you're not climbing, Doug?

82
00:06:18,980 --> 00:06:20,869
What, for work?
Yeah.

83
00:06:21,180 --> 00:06:23,706
Uh, different things.
Carpenter, mailman.

84
00:06:23,780 --> 00:06:25,669
Carpenter, mailman?

85
00:06:25,740 --> 00:06:26,741
Yep.

86
00:06:26,820 --> 00:06:28,151
Seriously,
you deliver the mail?

87
00:06:28,220 --> 00:06:29,745
Yeah, I deliver the mail.

88
00:06:31,420 --> 00:06:32,831
Mailman on Everest?

89
00:06:32,900 --> 00:06:34,425
Hope so.

90
00:06:34,500 --> 00:06:36,548
I like that.

91
00:06:36,620 --> 00:06:38,384
Mailman on Everest.

92
00:06:46,700 --> 00:06:47,701
There we go.

93
00:06:47,780 --> 00:06:49,111
- Beck.
- Yeah?

94
00:06:49,180 --> 00:06:51,501
You know he made it to the
South Summit on Everest last year?

95
00:06:51,580 --> 00:06:53,628
Who, Doug did?
Yeah.

96
00:06:53,740 --> 00:06:55,822
That's pretty
high for a mailman.

97
00:06:55,900 --> 00:06:59,347
Yep. Longs Peak, McKinley.

98
00:06:59,900 --> 00:07:02,631
I never made it up to
the top of McKinley myself.

99
00:07:02,700 --> 00:07:04,748
I know.
Well, how do you know that?

100
00:07:04,820 --> 00:07:06,185
'89, right?

101
00:07:06,700 --> 00:07:07,986
Oh!

102
00:07:08,180 --> 00:07:09,705
You've done your research.

103
00:07:09,780 --> 00:07:11,430
That's what we do.

104
00:07:19,300 --> 00:07:22,747
You, my friends, are following
in some very famous footsteps.

105
00:07:22,820 --> 00:07:24,868
A history made
famous by George Everest,

106
00:07:24,980 --> 00:07:27,904
George Mallory,
Tenzing Norgay,
Edmund Hillary.

107
00:07:27,980 --> 00:07:29,470
And Rob Hall!

108
00:07:32,820 --> 00:07:34,310
Legends all of them!

109
00:07:35,580 --> 00:07:37,070
That's right.

110
00:07:37,820 --> 00:07:39,540
For those of you who
dare face their dreams,

111
00:07:39,620 --> 00:07:40,906
Adventure Consultants
offers something

112
00:07:40,980 --> 00:07:44,063
beyond the power of
words to describe.

113
00:07:44,140 --> 00:07:47,508
And why don't we describe it
in the brochure?

114
00:07:48,220 --> 00:07:50,222
Because it's mostly
just pain.

115
00:07:50,300 --> 00:07:51,860
- Yes.
- Ain't that the truth?

116
00:07:51,900 --> 00:07:53,743
And the odd,
if you don't mind, Mike,

117
00:07:53,820 --> 00:07:55,822
and the odd missing toe.

118
00:07:57,340 --> 00:07:58,466
There we go.

119
00:08:00,340 --> 00:08:02,388
To put it simply,
guys, human beings

120
00:08:02,460 --> 00:08:04,622
simply aren't
built to function

121
00:08:04,700 --> 00:08:08,341
at the cruising
altitude of a 747.

122
00:08:08,780 --> 00:08:12,068
Okay, once we get above here,
above the South Col

123
00:08:12,140 --> 00:08:13,426
our bodies will be
literally dying.

124
00:08:13,500 --> 00:08:15,468
And I mean
literally dying.

125
00:08:15,540 --> 00:08:17,463
It's not called the Death Zone
for nothing, guys.

126
00:08:17,540 --> 00:08:18,541
So the game is,

127
00:08:18,900 --> 00:08:22,950
can we get you up to the top
and down to the bottom

128
00:08:23,020 --> 00:08:24,385
before that happens?

129
00:08:24,460 --> 00:08:26,189
- You sure can.
- Oh!

130
00:08:26,340 --> 00:08:28,183
Beck Weathers,
ladies and gentlemen.

131
00:08:28,260 --> 00:08:30,661
You might have noticed
a bit of the Lone Star State?

132
00:08:30,740 --> 00:08:32,265
100% Texan
right here, people.

133
00:08:32,380 --> 00:08:34,382
100% Texan.

134
00:08:35,340 --> 00:08:37,183
You've met Mike Groom.

135
00:08:37,700 --> 00:08:39,623
I'd like to introduce you
to Andy Harris.

136
00:08:39,700 --> 00:08:41,304
- Harold.
- Our other guide out of Queenstown.

137
00:08:41,380 --> 00:08:43,462
Taranaki, actually,
originally. <i>Kia ora.</i>

138
00:08:43,540 --> 00:08:46,146
Helen and the rest of the team
are already on the way up to Base Camp.

139
00:08:46,220 --> 00:08:48,427
They're setting it up
for when we get there.

140
00:08:48,500 --> 00:08:49,945
Today's March 30, people.

141
00:08:50,020 --> 00:08:52,022
I plan on going for
the summit May 10.

142
00:08:52,100 --> 00:08:54,626
It's been a lucky day for me
and Adventure Consultants

143
00:08:54,700 --> 00:08:57,101
and the weather's usually
pretty stable around then.

144
00:08:57,180 --> 00:08:58,341
So that means,

145
00:08:58,420 --> 00:09:01,981
we have 40 days to train
your bodies and your minds

146
00:09:02,060 --> 00:09:03,346
to go for it.

147
00:09:03,420 --> 00:09:06,469
Now, I know there's a lot of
mountaineering experience in this room.

148
00:09:06,580 --> 00:09:07,945
You wouldn't be
here without it.

149
00:09:08,020 --> 00:09:10,990
Stu, K2, Broad Peak.

150
00:09:11,060 --> 00:09:12,060
John Taske.

151
00:09:12,100 --> 00:09:14,626
1,192 meters of
Mount Kosciuszko.

152
00:09:16,060 --> 00:09:18,586
And... I mean,
Yasuko Namba.

153
00:09:18,700 --> 00:09:21,180
Six of the Seven Summits
and the only woman.

154
00:09:21,260 --> 00:09:22,260
There you go.

155
00:09:22,300 --> 00:09:23,825
Let's make it seven.
Thank you.

156
00:09:23,900 --> 00:09:27,461
But Everest, though, is another beast,
another beast altogether.

157
00:09:27,540 --> 00:09:29,349
That's why you're here,
isn't that right, Dougie?

158
00:09:29,420 --> 00:09:31,821
Oh, yeah. Yeah.

159
00:09:32,500 --> 00:09:35,663
So, listen. Tonight, that's it from me.
Eat, drink, be merry.

160
00:09:35,740 --> 00:09:37,105
Tomorrow, we trek.

161
00:09:39,780 --> 00:09:41,748
We good?
You ready for this?

162
00:09:43,580 --> 00:09:44,945
Dougie.

163
00:09:45,820 --> 00:09:47,709
All right,
folks, hang on.

164
00:09:47,780 --> 00:09:48,781
Okay.

165
00:09:48,860 --> 00:09:50,100
That's it,
here we go, Colonel.

166
00:09:50,180 --> 00:09:51,580
All right,
everybody, earbuds.

167
00:09:51,620 --> 00:09:53,622
Take your seats,
buckle in, everyone.

168
00:09:53,700 --> 00:09:54,701
Thanks, Mike.

169
00:09:55,620 --> 00:09:57,543
Do or die.
Here we go.

170
00:09:57,620 --> 00:09:58,781
Okay.

171
00:10:00,060 --> 00:10:01,266
Can you believe it?

172
00:10:01,340 --> 00:10:04,549
<i>Bravo 270 en route,
request Bravo 410.</i>

173
00:10:34,700 --> 00:10:35,906
Keep 'em all
in a nice group.

174
00:10:35,980 --> 00:10:37,106
Hey, guys,
take it easy.

175
00:10:38,340 --> 00:10:39,830
- Yes, I'm ready.
- Ready.

176
00:10:39,900 --> 00:10:41,629
We're kicking
it off, let's go.

177
00:10:41,700 --> 00:10:43,543
You lead
the way, pal.

178
00:10:44,380 --> 00:10:45,620
You all right?

179
00:10:45,700 --> 00:10:46,826
Yes.

180
00:11:21,060 --> 00:11:23,301
Guys, man wants to
see your climbing permits.

181
00:11:23,380 --> 00:11:25,508
Need to see all your
climbing permits!

182
00:11:25,580 --> 00:11:27,787
<i>Namaste.</i>

183
00:11:27,860 --> 00:11:29,464
Thank you very much,
we'll see you on the way back.

184
00:11:29,540 --> 00:11:31,190
Thank you very much.

185
00:11:31,300 --> 00:11:33,462
All good?
Yeah, yeah.
Yeah, you?

186
00:11:33,540 --> 00:11:35,110
Yeah.
Hey, uh...

187
00:11:35,900 --> 00:11:37,345
Thanks, Rob.

188
00:11:37,780 --> 00:11:39,020
Thanks for what?

189
00:11:39,100 --> 00:11:40,704
You know, the discount.

190
00:11:41,940 --> 00:11:44,386
Well, you're working
three jobs, Doug.

191
00:11:44,460 --> 00:11:45,461
It was the least
I could do, mate.

192
00:11:45,540 --> 00:11:48,987
I know, you didn't have to do it,
though, and I appreciate it.

193
00:11:50,700 --> 00:11:52,350
Let's just get you
to the top this time.

194
00:11:52,420 --> 00:11:53,706
Yeah.

195
00:12:04,340 --> 00:12:06,229
How you feeling, Beck?

196
00:12:07,060 --> 00:12:08,505
Fair to middling.

197
00:12:08,580 --> 00:12:10,469
Come on, buddy,
you can do it.

198
00:12:10,540 --> 00:12:12,460
Thought I was gonna
acclimatize faster than this.

199
00:12:12,540 --> 00:12:14,781
Uh, you'll be all right.

200
00:12:17,260 --> 00:12:18,750
Darn critters.

201
00:12:34,220 --> 00:12:35,221
Whoo!

202
00:12:36,660 --> 00:12:38,503
Wow.
Yeah.

203
00:12:44,180 --> 00:12:45,591
How close
did you get?

204
00:12:45,660 --> 00:12:48,869
Well, I got real close
but it got late and I was

205
00:12:48,940 --> 00:12:50,704
pretty shot anyways.

206
00:12:51,780 --> 00:12:53,987
Well, I think I would
have made a run for it.

207
00:12:54,100 --> 00:12:55,431
Every day I wake
up thinking that.

208
00:12:55,500 --> 00:12:57,025
Then why didn't you do it?

209
00:12:57,100 --> 00:12:58,431
'Cause I
turned him around.

210
00:12:59,340 --> 00:13:00,865
Morning 15 at
the South Summit,

211
00:13:00,980 --> 00:13:01,981
bad conditions,

212
00:13:02,060 --> 00:13:04,666
we weren't gonna make
our 2:00 p.m. turnaround.

213
00:13:04,740 --> 00:13:06,390
See, it's all good and well
to make the top, Beck,

214
00:13:06,460 --> 00:13:08,827
but you pay me to
bring you down safely.

215
00:13:08,900 --> 00:13:10,629
Remember that.

216
00:13:11,700 --> 00:13:12,826
Okay.

217
00:13:22,180 --> 00:13:23,864
What's eating him?

218
00:13:24,700 --> 00:13:27,351
One of our Sherpas, Tenzing.
He had an accident.

219
00:13:27,420 --> 00:13:29,184
Oh, yeah?
Yeah.

220
00:13:29,740 --> 00:13:31,629
Fell while fixing one of
the ladders on the Icefall.

221
00:13:31,700 --> 00:13:34,829
It's not good.
They had to bring him down.

222
00:14:16,060 --> 00:14:17,346
<i>Namaste.</i>

223
00:14:21,700 --> 00:14:22,701
<i>Namaste.</i>

224
00:15:19,780 --> 00:15:23,307
Congratulations, you all made it.
Welcome to Base Camp!

225
00:15:23,380 --> 00:15:25,348
We got the United
Nations here this year.

226
00:15:25,460 --> 00:15:27,940
Got the IMAX team,
South Africans.

227
00:15:30,420 --> 00:15:32,024
And right up here

228
00:15:33,580 --> 00:15:35,469
in the best spot of all

229
00:15:36,220 --> 00:15:38,063
we have the Adventure
Consultants Base Camp.

230
00:15:38,180 --> 00:15:40,501
Hey, Helen.
Hey. Hi, how are you?

231
00:15:40,620 --> 00:15:43,624
Good to see you.
Thank you.
Welcome, nice to see you.

232
00:15:43,700 --> 00:15:44,747
Hi, Rob.
Hey.

233
00:15:44,820 --> 00:15:46,424
Well done,
you all right?

234
00:15:46,500 --> 00:15:47,547
Yeah, good. You?

235
00:15:47,620 --> 00:15:50,146
- Yeah, no, we're good.
- It looks good.

236
00:15:50,220 --> 00:15:52,541
For those of you that haven't met,
this is Helen Wilton,

237
00:15:52,620 --> 00:15:53,985
Base Camp manager.

238
00:15:54,060 --> 00:15:57,587
She will be your mom
for the next few weeks.

239
00:15:57,700 --> 00:15:59,580
Any problems, take it to
her and she'll sort it.

240
00:15:59,660 --> 00:16:01,947
All right, well,
it's very nice

241
00:16:02,020 --> 00:16:03,670
to finally meet
you all in person.

242
00:16:03,780 --> 00:16:05,225
Ang Dorjee, come here.

243
00:16:05,300 --> 00:16:06,984
This is Ang Dorjee,
everyone.

244
00:16:07,060 --> 00:16:09,745
He's your climbing <i>sirdar,</i>
your lead Sherpa.

245
00:16:10,260 --> 00:16:11,864
Hey, how are ya?

246
00:16:11,940 --> 00:16:13,101
You speak English?

247
00:16:13,140 --> 00:16:16,349
Better than you, Mr. America.

248
00:16:16,460 --> 00:16:18,940
Bet you climb better than I do, huh?
Yeah.

249
00:16:19,620 --> 00:16:20,701
Yeah?

250
00:16:21,620 --> 00:16:22,985
Summited three times, Beck.

251
00:16:23,100 --> 00:16:24,511
All right, all right.
I hear ya, I hear ya.

252
00:16:24,580 --> 00:16:26,548
All right, well, there's
tea in the mess tent

253
00:16:26,620 --> 00:16:28,827
when you've
dumped your sacks

254
00:16:29,380 --> 00:16:30,745
and the comms
tent's down the back,

255
00:16:30,820 --> 00:16:33,107
that's the cooking tent,
and over there

256
00:16:33,180 --> 00:16:34,670
is the toilet.

257
00:16:35,220 --> 00:16:38,781
It's a little bit drafty,
but just remember that

