at Everest Base Camp!

291
00:18:05,900 --> 00:18:07,584
She one of yours?
Oh, yeah.

292
00:18:07,660 --> 00:18:09,549
Someone went and
stole my journalist

293
00:18:09,620 --> 00:18:11,588
so I had to get another one.
Hmm.

294
00:18:11,660 --> 00:18:14,186
She's a lot easier on the eye
than Jon Krakauer,

295
00:18:14,260 --> 00:18:15,466
that's for sure.
Listen, just to be clear,

296
00:18:15,540 --> 00:18:16,587
I didn't steal
your journalist.

297
00:18:16,660 --> 00:18:17,707
Hey, man, it's all good.

298
00:18:17,780 --> 00:18:20,101
<i>Outside</i> magazine
gave me a call.

299
00:18:20,180 --> 00:18:21,705
Hey. Hey!
They gave me a call.

300
00:18:21,780 --> 00:18:23,782
- Said they wanted to...
- It's all good, man.

301
00:18:23,860 --> 00:18:25,146
They were gonna send
a journalist up the hill

302
00:18:25,220 --> 00:18:28,463
and asked me if
I was interested.

303
00:18:29,060 --> 00:18:31,142
It was his call
in the end.

304
00:18:41,540 --> 00:18:43,110
All right, Caroline MacKenzie,
team doctor.

305
00:18:43,180 --> 00:18:44,705
Why don't you
kick it off, Caro.

306
00:18:44,780 --> 00:18:46,509
- Hi, everyone.
- Hey, Caro.

307
00:18:46,620 --> 00:18:47,860
Hi there.

308
00:18:49,380 --> 00:18:51,542
Sorry.
That's fine.

309
00:18:51,660 --> 00:18:52,661
Um...

310
00:18:52,980 --> 00:18:55,062
So Rob and Harold
and Mike will tell you

311
00:18:55,140 --> 00:18:57,222
all sorts of stuff
about mountaineering,

312
00:18:57,300 --> 00:18:59,268
but from a
medical standpoint

313
00:18:59,380 --> 00:19:02,907
getting you to the top of Everest
is really about oxygen.

314
00:19:02,980 --> 00:19:04,630
And the lack of it.

315
00:19:04,700 --> 00:19:06,589
To give you the best
chance of summiting

316
00:19:06,660 --> 00:19:08,310
you need to
prepare your bodies

317
00:19:08,380 --> 00:19:09,950
for the thin air up there.

318
00:19:10,060 --> 00:19:12,711
So, over the next month,
before the final ascent

319
00:19:12,780 --> 00:19:15,704
you're gonna make three
partial acclimatizing ascents

320
00:19:15,780 --> 00:19:18,021
returning here to
Base Camp after each one.

321
00:19:18,740 --> 00:19:20,629
<i>The bad news is
that each ascent</i>

322
00:19:20,700 --> 00:19:22,543
<i>begins and ends
with the Icefall.</i>

323
00:19:23,180 --> 00:19:26,263
<i>I'm sorry, but there
is no way around it.</i>

324
00:19:26,340 --> 00:19:28,263
<i>There are millions
of tons of glacial ice</i>

325
00:19:28,340 --> 00:19:30,627
<i>continually moving
day and night.</i>

326
00:19:30,700 --> 00:19:32,668
<i>You got seracs
the size of tower blocks,</i>

327
00:19:32,740 --> 00:19:36,347
you got crevasses so deep
they probably don't even have a bottom.

328
00:19:36,460 --> 00:19:38,861
It is not a place that
you wanna get caught hanging out in,

329
00:19:38,940 --> 00:19:40,624
especially when
the sun hits it.

330
00:19:40,700 --> 00:19:41,906
So we're gonna be
up nice and early

331
00:19:41,980 --> 00:19:44,187
and through that
as soon as possible.

332
00:19:44,300 --> 00:19:45,506
Now the Sherpas
have gone ahead

333
00:19:45,580 --> 00:19:46,991
<i>and fixed the ladders
across the crevasses</i>

334
00:19:47,060 --> 00:19:49,427
<i>and we've made it as
safe as we possibly can.</i>

335
00:19:49,500 --> 00:19:51,707
<i>But that is not to say
that it is completely safe.</i>

336
00:19:52,340 --> 00:19:55,071
<i>19 people have
died in that Icefall.</i>

337
00:19:55,660 --> 00:19:58,061
Whoa!
Whoa! Hold on!

338
00:19:59,260 --> 00:20:00,591
Steady.

339
00:20:00,660 --> 00:20:01,866
You all right, Jon?

340
00:20:01,940 --> 00:20:03,544
You all right?

341
00:20:03,620 --> 00:20:04,906
- I'm good.
- Okay.

342
00:20:04,980 --> 00:20:06,789
All right, steady up.
Whoo!

343
00:20:06,860 --> 00:20:09,431
<i>So remember,
we're a team.</i>

344
00:20:09,500 --> 00:20:11,104
<i>Let's look out for each other.</i>

345
00:20:12,460 --> 00:20:14,189
<i>Look out
for hypothermia,</i>

346
00:20:14,260 --> 00:20:16,991
<i>things like slurred speech
and irrational behavior.</i>

347
00:20:17,940 --> 00:20:19,669
<i>I've seen hypoxic
climbers rip off</i>

348
00:20:19,740 --> 00:20:21,390
<i>all their clothes
at 8,000 meters</i>

349
00:20:21,460 --> 00:20:23,588
<i>because they're feeling hot.</i>

350
00:20:24,980 --> 00:20:27,790
You all know about cerebral edema,
the swelling of your brain

351
00:20:27,860 --> 00:20:31,069
to the point of loss of motor
function and eventually death.

352
00:20:32,660 --> 00:20:35,903
<i>And pulmonary edema,
which is your lungs filling with fluid</i>

353
00:20:36,020 --> 00:20:38,022
<i>so you effectively drown.</i>

354
00:20:38,100 --> 00:20:40,785
<i>The only cure is to get
down the mountain, fast.</i>

355
00:20:41,540 --> 00:20:43,110
- All right, okay.
- All right, buddy.

356
00:20:43,180 --> 00:20:45,626
<i>But it is not all
doom and gloom here, okay?</i>

357
00:20:45,700 --> 00:20:47,543
<i>Myself and
the whole AC team are here</i>

358
00:20:47,620 --> 00:20:49,429
<i>to make sure you get
up and down safely</i>

359
00:20:49,500 --> 00:20:52,231
<i>and you will
acclimatize naturally.</i>

360
00:20:52,300 --> 00:20:55,144
So why don't we all
give Caro a nice big thank you,

361
00:20:55,220 --> 00:20:56,426
it's her
first time here.

362
00:20:57,260 --> 00:20:59,467
- All right.
- Nice job.

363
00:21:10,500 --> 00:21:11,831
Well done.

364
00:21:12,180 --> 00:21:13,989
See, you want to
get on the regulator.

365
00:21:14,100 --> 00:21:15,147
You want to
hear that hiss.

366
00:21:17,620 --> 00:21:18,701
Connect your hose.

367
00:21:18,780 --> 00:21:20,703
- Yasuko.
- Beck.

368
00:21:20,780 --> 00:21:22,225
How'd you do, darling?
Okay.

369
00:21:22,300 --> 00:21:23,904
- Good?
- Well done.

370
00:21:23,980 --> 00:21:24,981
Can I get a hit of that?

371
00:21:25,060 --> 00:21:27,108
Have a suck on that.

372
00:21:27,180 --> 00:21:28,740
In a situation like this,
you just wanna

373
00:21:28,780 --> 00:21:30,908
catch your breath,
throw it up to four.

